## What Happened

**`DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS** because Apple's native cryptographic frameworks (Security.framework / CryptoKit) have never supported the legacy DSA algorithm. In earlier .NET versions, the runtime fell back to an OpenSSL interop shim on macOS to provide DSA. .NET 11 removed that fallback, aligning macOS with the platform-native-only crypto policy that was signaled by the `SYSLIB0030` obsolescence warning added in prior releases.

Linux still works because it uses OpenSSL natively. Windows still works because CNG supports DSA.

## How to Fix

You have two options:

### Option 1 — Use BouncyCastle (recommended if you must keep verifying DSA signatures)

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

```csharp
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

public static bool VerifyDsaSignature(byte[] data, byte[] signature, AsymmetricKeyParameter publicKey)
{
    var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA1withDSA");
    verifier.Init(forSigning: false, publicKey);
    verifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
    return verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
}
```

This is a pure managed implementation — no platform-native dependency, so it works on all three OSes.

### Option 2 — Migrate away from DSA entirely (recommended long-term)

Re-sign your artifacts with a modern algorithm (e.g., **ECDSA** or **Ed25519**). DSA key sizes are capped at 1024 bits in most implementations and the algorithm has been deprecated by NIST since 2013.

### Summary

| | Linux | Windows | macOS |
|---|---|---|---|
| `DSA.Create()` .NET 10 | ✅ OpenSSL | ✅ CNG | ✅ OpenSSL shim |
| `DSA.Create()` .NET 11 | ✅ OpenSSL | ✅ CNG | ❌ **Removed** |
| BouncyCastle | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ |

If this is verification-only for legacy data, BouncyCastle is the lowest-effort fix. If you control both signing and verification, migrate to ECDSA.
